<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-610-845  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 610 845.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC-Computing  Dec 1990 v3 n12 p196(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>At last, a PATH editor. (Hot Tip: Startup)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Uribe, Luis.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT/><TEXT>At Last, a PATH Editor If you're constantly adding and deleting applications,you're constantly modifying your AUTOEXEC.BAT PATH statement.andP;  Your PATH is avariable that DOS stores in a chunk of RAM known as the environment space.andO;Unfortunately, you can't easily edit items stored in the environment.andP;  Thefollowing batch file, PE.BAT, makes it a snap to store your PATH statement ina batch file, which is easy to edit.andM;PATH andgt; OLDPATH.andP;  BAT PATH andgt; NEWPATH.BAT EDITOR NEWPATH.BAT CALL NEWPATH.BATPATH DEL NEWPATH.BATandM;The first line creates a backup copy of your PATH by storing it in a batchfile called OLDPATH.BAT.andP;  To reinstall the old version, type OLDPATH at theDOS prompt.andM;The second line stores a second copy of the PATH in NEWPATH.BAT.andP;  The thirdline invokes your ASCII text editor, EDITOR, and tells it to editNEWPATH.BAT, which contains your PATH.andP;  Substitute the command that invokesyour editor for EDITOR in the batch file.andP;  (This program assumes that youreditor will load a file from the command line.)andM;After you've modified your PATH, exit EDITOR.andP;  PE.BAT executes NEWPATH.BAT,which uses the PATH command to install your new PATH.andP;  (If you have DOSVersion 3.2 or earlier, substitute COMMAND /C for the CALL command.)andM;Line 5 displays your current PATH and line 6 deletes NEWPATH.BAT, which is nolonger needed.andO;</TEXT></DOC>